=====Usage notes=====
The original Chinese word for “moving water source” such as "brook", "river", etc. was {{zh-l|水}}, literally “water”. The original glyph had three strokes showing water in the middle flowing from land embankments to its sides.

With the sophistication of culture, complex layers of words and subtle differences in meanings evolved. In time, the moving water bodies were differentiated based on their sizes and moving water speeds. 

The proper name {{zh-l|河}} was used as a word for rivers that are bigger than brooks and its original bearer distinguished as the {{zh-l|黃河|[[Yellow River]]}} which is an older water source with a smaller volume of moving water. Similarly, {{lang|zh|江}} was originally the name of the [[Yangtze]] [[river|River]] a larger moving water source and then became the standard bearer for this differentiated term. It was then applied broadly as a generic word for rivers of this size category. 

Nowadays, in modern Standard Mandarin, {{lang|zh|江}} are usually the larger rivers, {{zh-l|*河}} are older dried up rivers, and 溪 are [[creek]]s, and 流 are [[brook]]s and {{zh-l|*水}} are [[stream]]s; but there are exceptions to this general pattern owing to historical reasons and the cultural incompatibility in the translation between Modern English and Modern Mandarin.

